article.headline: Wake Forest 92, Gardner-Webb 60
article.story: WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) -- Practices haven't been much fun for Wake Forest recently, especially after losing four straight games. But things may be better for the Demon Deacons this week after they posted season highs in four offensive categories during a 92-60 victory over Gardner-Webb on Tuesday night. Kyle Visser, Michael Drum and freshman Anthony Gurley each scored 13 points for Wake Forest (6-4), which went through the entire bench in posting its highest-scoring game and largest margin of victory this season. "Everything's OK (in practice) when you're winning, but when you're losing it becomes very tough," said Drum, one of 12 Wake Forest players to score Tuesday. "Everybody wants to win, but we've come up short lately. This game ought to get us back on the right track." Wake Forest shot 66.7 percent from the field, the fifth-best game in school history that included a 10-of-15 effort from 3-point range after the team went 18-of-68 during its recent losing streak. "We finally hit on all cylinders," Visser said. "That's something we haven't had, especially the last four games. That's part of the reason those games were losses. ... But we were getting offense from all over the place tonight." Ricky McPhee scored 12 points for the Bulldogs (2-8), who fell to 0-8 against Atlantic Coast Conference teams -- including an 0-3 mark this season -- since the program stepped up to Division I in 2000. Takayo Siddle and Thomas Sanders added 11 points each, and Jake Sims and Chris Gash had 10 each for Gardner-Webb, which also lost this season to then-No. 2 North Carolina and North Carolina State. The Demon Deacons overcame a season-high 21 turnovers with their shooting touch and a decided advantage inside, outrebounding the smaller Bulldogs 37-26 and outscoring them 38-20 in the paint. Wake Forest also had 28 assists, tying for third-best in school history. "This was a feel-good game when we needed a feel-good game," Demon Deacons head coach Skip Prosser said. "We've had a tough road these last four games ... so it was nice to be able to reward some of the kids with some playing time. It's good to see other guys get some points." Wake Forest led from nearly the start of the game, but Gardner-Webb managed to close the gap to 14-12 on Gash's 3-pointer with 11:15 left in the first half. Wake Forest responded with an 18-0 run, with Kevin Swinton's tip-in putting the Demon Deacons up 32-12 with 7:16 remaining. "We knew they were going to be hungry," Bulldogs head coach Rick Scruggs said. "We came out playing pretty confident, pretty loose ... then they went on that run. "When you're making shots, everything seems to fall into place. They made shots and we didn't. There's not much more you can say about it." Wake Forest increased its lead to 47-23 at the break, then took its biggest lead late in the second half when Gurley hit back-to-back 3-pointers to put the Demon Deacons up 90-55 with 1:50 left. "We kind of got down on ourselves ... so it's always great to get a win to get out of that," said Wake Forest freshman guard Ish Smith, who had a team-high seven assists. "When you're out there being unselfish and just playing basketball, it becomes a lot more fun. When we play defense like that, we're going to be tough to beat."
